The paper deals with image forensics, specifically constrained image splicing detection and localization, which involves identifying whether one image has suspected regions pasted from the other. This falls under the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper proposes a novel adversarial learning framework to train a deep matching network based on atrous convolution, which involves generating high-quality candidate masks, detecting inconsistencies, and driving the network to produce masks that are hard to distinguish from ground-truth ones. This involves machine learning (cs.LG) and possibly multimedia (cs.MM) techniques. The paper also involves evaluating the proposed framework on generated testing sets and two public datasets, which involves performance evaluation (cs.IR) and potentially cryptography and security (cs.CR) techniques.
